Data Clean-Up: Historic Data

Letâs pare down the Alaska Swan Database data set to fit our needs.

First, letâs load our packages, import the data, and put it into a data frame for manipulation. Uncomment the first line to install missing packages.

#install.packages(c("knitr", "corrplot"))
library(knitr)
library(corrplot)
corrplot 0.95 loaded
old_df <- read.csv("swanDb.csv")

Next, letâs subset the data to only include Tetlin NWR quads, â¦

map1_quads <- c("A2", "A3", "A4", "B4", "B5", "B6")
map2_quads <- c("B1", "B2", "C1", "C2", "C3", "D1", "D2", "D3", "D4")
old_df <- old_df[which(((old_df$Map == 69) & (old_df$Quad %in% map1_quads)) | ((old_df$Map == 78) & (old_df$Quad %in% map2_quads))),]

â¦remove data from early summer (May, June) nesting surveys and years with little data (pre-1985), â¦

old_df <- old_df[which((old_df$Month != 5) & (old_df$Month != 6)), ]
old_df <- old_df[which(old_df$Year >= 1985), ]

â¦and remove unnecessary columns, such as those for nesting data (which we are not looking at) or quarter quad numbers (which were never utilized at Tetlin).

old_df <- subset(old_df, select = -c(X, QtrQuad, Nest, Map, Quad))

Data Clean-Up: New Data

Now, letâs format the new data to match the historic data.

Letâs begin again by importing.

new_df <- read.csv("newswans_2022.csv")

Next, weâll remove null-valued rowsâ¦

new_df <- new_df[which(new_df$TOTAL != 0),]

â¦and remove extra or unnecessary columns.

new_df <- subset(new_df, select = -c(TOTAL, Pairs, ele, name, ID))

We also need to separate out flocks observed with other group types into separate, individual observations (rows). We are going to adjust the latitude value of these ânewâ observations with an increase of 0.0001.

for(i in 1:nrow(new_df)){
  count = 0
  if((new_df$GroupSize[i] > 0) && (new_df$PAIRSX2[i] > 0)){
    count = count + 1
    addRow <- new_df[i,]
    addRow$GroupSize <- 0
    addRow$Singles <- 0
    addRow$lat <- addRow$lat + count/10000
    new_df <- rbind(new_df, addRow)
    new_df$PAIRSX2[i] <- 0
  }
  if((new_df$GroupSize[i] > 0) && (new_df$Singles[i] > 0)){
    count = count + 1
    addRow <- new_df[i,]
    addRow$GroupSize <- 0
    addRow$PAIRSX2 <- 0
    addRow$lat <- addRow$lat + count/10000
    new_df <- rbind(new_df, addRow)
    new_df$Singles[i] <- 0
  }
}

To match the historic data, weâll add columns for the numbers of adults and young per observation.

new_df$Adults <- new_df$GroupSize + new_df$PAIRSX2 + new_df$Singles
new_df$Young <- new_df$Cygnets

We also need to create a new symbology column to identify the group type for each observation. The abbreviations used are as follows: âSâ for single no brood, âPâ for pair no brood, âSBrâ for single with brood, âPBrâ for pair with brood, âFâ for flock, and â0Brâ for lone cygnets.

new_df$Leg_Sym <- NA
for(i in 1:nrow(new_df)){
  if(new_df$Singles[i] > 0){
    if(new_df$Cygnets[i] > 0){
      new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "SBr"
    }else{
      new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "S"
    }
  }else if(new_df$PAIRSX2[i] > 0){
    if(new_df$Cygnets[i] > 0){
      new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "PBr"
    }else{
      new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "P"
    }
  }else if(new_df$GroupSize[i] > 0){
    new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "F"
  }else{
    new_df$Leg_Sym[i] <- "0Br"
  }
}

Now, we can remove columns that were captured by the new symbology column.

new_df <- subset(new_df, select = -c(Singles, PAIRSX2, Cygnets, GroupSize))

We will separate out the date column into individual columns for the day, month, and year.

new_df$Month <- as.numeric(substr(new_df$time, 6, 7))
new_df$Day <- as.numeric(substr(new_df$time, 9, 10))
new_df$Year <- as.numeric(substr(new_df$time, 1, 4))
new_df <- subset(new_df, select = -time)

The final tweaks require adding a contributor number column and capitalizing the âlatâ and âlonâ column headers for consistency.

colnames(new_df)[which(colnames(new_df) == "lat")] <- "Lat"
colnames(new_df)[which(colnames(new_df) == "lon")] <- "Lon"
new_df$Contrib <- rep(108,times=nrow(new_df))

Combine Old and New Data

We are ready to combine our data sets.

combined_df <- rbind(old_df, new_df)

Retrieve New Summary Calculations

summarize <- function(df){
  years <- sort(unique(df$Year), decreasing = FALSE)
  years <- years[which(years >= 1985)]
  
  total_swans <- c()
  total_adults <- c()
  breeding_adults <- c()
  total_broods <- c()
  total_cygnets <- c()
  
  for (val in years){
    total_swans <- append(total_swans, sum(df$Adults[which(df$Year == val)], df$Young[which(df$Year == val)]))
    total_adults <- append(total_adults, sum(df$Adults[which(df$Year == val)]))
    breeding_adults <- append(breeding_adults, sum(df$Adults[which(df$Year == val & (df$Leg_Sym == "PBr" | df$Leg_Sym == "SBr"))]))
    total_broods <- append(total_broods, length(which(df$Year == val & df$Young > 1)))
    total_cygnets <- append(total_cygnets, sum(df$Young[which(df$Year == val)]))
  }
  
  proportion_breeding <- breeding_adults/total_adults
  avg_brood_size <- total_cygnets/total_broods
  
  annual_growth_rate <- c(0)
  for (i in 2:length(total_swans)){
    rate <- round((total_swans[i]/total_swans[i-1])^(1/(years[i]-years[i-1]))-1, digits=4)
    annual_growth_rate <- append(annual_growth_rate, rate)
  }
  
  summary_df <- data.frame(years, total_swans, annual_growth_rate, breeding_adults, proportion_breeding, total_broods, total_cygnets, avg_brood_size)
  return(summary_df)
}

Example Report

Letâs get some variables prepared.

df <- summarize(buffer_df)
index <- which(df$years == max(df$years))
current_year <- df$years[index]
start_month <- min(unique(combined_df$Month[which(combined_df$Year == current_year)]))
start_day <- min(unique(combined_df$Day[which(combined_df$Year == current_year & combined_df$Month == start_month)]))
end_month <- max(unique(combined_df$Month[which(combined_df$Year == current_year)]))
end_day <- max(unique(combined_df$Day[which(combined_df$Year == current_year & combined_df$Month == end_month)]))
if(df$total_swans[index] > df$total_swans[index-1]){
  total_change <- "increase"
}else{
  total_change <- "decrease"
}
if(df$total_swans[index] > df$total_swans[index-1]){
  breeding_change <- "increased"
}else{
  breeding_change <- "decreased"
}

Here is what that report can look like:

In 2022, the trumpeter swan census survey was flown from 8/16 to 8/18. 1103 total swans were counted during the survey, which is a 39.3% decrease since the previous survey flown in 2015. The population growth rate since the last survey was about -6.88% annually.

Of the 916 adults, 141, or 15.39%, were deemed to be breeding. The proportion of reproducing adults decreased by about 3.58% since the previous survey. There were 187 observed cygnets and 47 total broods, corresponding to an average brood size of about 3.98 cygnets.
